metadata.name: Missplaced #69
metadata.description:
Being in a space, knowing that we are enveloped by an object—a ground or a wall—made us aware of our external reality. And when a space gains social, cultural, or emotional meaning, it becomes a place.

But sometimes, these spaces and places betray us, isolating the inhabitants who live in them, as if every room and ground are turning hostile and apathetic to the beings who live within its own walls.

In the end, as a way to confirm our being, we are wired to belong to a place, whether it's a theoretical place or a physical place. This feeling of being misplaced can happen even in the most hospitable places in the universe.

------------
11 Color Palette
4 Variant of "Home"
4 Variant of "Environment"
and some Planetary

metadata.name: Swedish Forest #253
metadata.description:
If I had to choose a place where time was frozen and where I could contemplate the landscape for eternity this place would be a scandinavian forest.
I have been contemplating these kind of landscape for a very long time both in Sweden and in the Pyrenees where the ecosystem is very similar.
This project generates an illustration of a scandinavian forest in many different situations. At day and at night, in every season of the year, next to a lake or not, with steep hills or at the plains, snowing, with preponderance of some plant species over others, etc.
The artwork is also drawn in various paint modes and layouts.

The sun or the moon may be visible, the moon shows always the actual moon phase based on the current date.
The reflection on the lake is the fxhash morse endcoded.


Developed in vanilla js using svg and canvas
Rendering can be unresponsive on slow devices
Click or touch to switch to Parallax mode, just move the mouse or finger.


[S] Download in SVG format
[D] Download in PNG format

Features:

Layout: Landscape, Portrait, Square
PredominantSpecies: Blueberry, Lingonberry, Calluna, Rocks, None
Trees: Mixed, PinesAndFirs, Birches, None
Season: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter
DayNight: Day, Night
PaintStyle: Normal, Stroke, Paint, WhiteOnBlack, BlackOnWhite
ColorStyle: Normal, Crazy
HasLake: True, False
HasTrees: None, Few, Many, Crowded

metadata.name: Happenings #56
metadata.description:
Inspired by the chaos and imperfectly beautiful dynamics of parenting and life, 'Happenings' is the embodiment of the messiness, the unexpected and playful experiences that allow for the greatest depths of connection with our children.

Our intention was to evoke our deepest and most personal feelings as parents of young ones navigating the challenges of the pandemic while immersing ourselves in the Web3 arena.

This collection is Jimena + Marcos’ first generative art collection in the Tezos blockchain via FX Hash, and consists of 222 1/1 artworks created with javascript.

metadata.name: Handachak #86
metadata.description:
I have always been looking for solutions that can connect different visual elements in such a way as to create an integrated system and structure and each part of the work plays its own role in this system.
Another point is that always attributing physical characteristics to abstract forms creates aesthetic qualities. From a general point of view, one of these features is perspective, and in this project we see a type of perspective in an abstract and geometric structure.
"Handachak" means "Geometry" in ancient Persian.

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #346
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS #220
metadata.description:
EPIHYPERDERPFLARDIOIDS

after symbol 2525, 
aint gonna need to load, write no code
everything you think, do and say
is in the streams that you watch today (oh oh oh)

We find this code is very much alive. They are epi. They are hyper. They are derp. They are flardioids.

Epihyperderpflardioids is the name I have given to a large family of symmetrical loopy shapes, based on sine waves and rotations, reminiscent of the mathematical toy game "Spirograph", but also different. I studied them extensively, but don't claim to understand them fully, yet. I hope you enjoy them as much as I do.

These 365 Epihyperderpflardioids were generated for FXhash's one year anniversary.

metadata.name: Isola della Scala #84

All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

metadata.name: For Algernon #214
metadata.description:
I brought flowers for Algernon, but some are lost to time
When logic gives way to emotions and order surrenders to entropy
For lost youths and forgotten dreams
Someday there may be flowers for me

This work is inspired by the brilliant short story Flowers for Algernon. I read the story for the first time last year, cried, then immediately started working on this series. The initial painting process cannot be paused; this is my intention and not an oversight. You may watch the perfect moment slip by, but I hope that you’ll come to love the end result as well. There is beauty in imperfection, and everything that is remembered is not entirely lost. After the initial painting is complete, you can press [p] to watch it continuously evolve.

I developed two new original algorithms for this work. First, a method to draw flowers by rotating and layering sine waves at varying amplitudes and wavelengths to create a variety of colored petals. Second, a real-time painting method with multisampling to blend and generate new colors on the fly. The first method represents order, logic and the intellect, while the second represents entropy, chance, and emotions. Together, this is a study of generative flowers under entropy, where strokes are allowed to wander and colors to mix freely. I didn’t set out to emulate any traditional media, but the outputs of this algorithm often resemble acrylic paintings at first glance. Upon closer inspection you will discover that each painting is entirely made of opaque geometric strokes that are distinctly digital. 

This work is best viewed in a Chrome or Edge browser on a desktop machine, where the initial painting process only takes a few seconds. The rendering in Safari and Firefox is significantly slower as of January 2023. Made with p5js and the canvas API.

Keyboard controls:
[p] Play/pause painting after the initial rendering is completed.
[f] Fill the current window (press ‘f’ again to get back to the original aspect ratio).
[g] Toggle the background texture.
[m] Change the margin amount. 
[s] Saves a PNG image of the live view, default resolution is 1600x2000px.
[1]-[6] Change the output resolution, up to 9600x12000px. 

URL parameters:
&aspect=[an aspect ratio between 0.25 and 4, default is 0.8]
&texture=[a roughness value greater than or equal to 0, default is 1]
&margin=[the amount of margin around the painting (try 20 to 150), default is 0]
&fill=[true/false, whether to fill the window]

Created by Elsif, 2023.01.

P.S. Someday I may no longer understand all the code I wrote, but there will always be an impression of colors, and a memory of flowers.

metadata.name: DEGREES OF FREEDOM #23
metadata.description:
Forms constricted to a plane, yearning to be free. Multitudes of expression, endless possibilities of shapes, the inevitable hissing rising from the dreaded empty page.

This piece is inspired by the Futurists' concept of 'universal dynamism' - the idea that separations between objects and their contexts are an illusion and time makes any distinctions meaningless. It tries to capture the expressivity of the moving object along all its potential vectors.

This piece evolved from my #genuary piece for 'Minimalism' (which was even then more surrealism than anything else). DEGREES OF FREEDOM is minted as part of #genuary32nd.

Press 'S' to take a screenshot. Recommended resolution: 2400 x 3000 pixels.
Written in JavaScript without libraries, February 2023.
